          "body": "2 Samuel 13 is a chapter where God is never mentioned by name, yet the entire narrative is saturated with divine governance. The pattern of Nathan's oracle is running precisely on schedule. The narrator's refusal to editorialize — no 'and this was evil in the sight of the LORD,' no explicit divine judgment — is not indifference; it is the confidence that the reader will supply the verdict from the Mosaic law (Leviticus 18:9; Deuteronomy 22:25-29) and the preceding oracle. There is, however, one figure to whom no one renders justice in this chapter: Tamar. Amnon violates her, Absalom silences her ('keep silent, my sister,' 13:20), David never acts on her behalf, and the narrator moves on to Absalom's revenge without reporting any restoration for her. She ends the chapter *shamem* — desolate — and disappears from the narrative. Orthodox commentators including Peter Craigie and Walter Brueggemann have observed that this is itself part of the narrator's indictment: the men of the chapter orbit around power and succession; the woman most wronged is the one the narrative buries. But the canon does not forget her. The same God who 'saw the affliction' of Hagar (Genesis 16:13) and whose name in Numbers 27 vindicates the daughters of Zelophehad is the God against whose law Amnon acted and whose sovereignty is present even in the chapters where He does not speak. The sword that never departs from David's house has entered — but the God who sent Nathan also numbers the hairs of Tamar's head."
