        "excerpt": "So Tamar remained and was desolate in her brother Absalom's house.",
        "body": "The aftermath of the assault is narrated with spare, devastating economy. Amnon calls his servant and uses language appropriate for disposing of property — 'throw this woman out of my presence' (13:17). The dehumanizing pronoun 'this woman' (*zot*) where he earlier called her 'my sister' marks the complete collapse of relational identity in Amnon's mind. The door is bolted behind her — the same door through which she entered faithfully carrying food.\n\nThe torn robe in vv. 18-19 is the chapter's most powerful visual image. The long-sleeved garment (*ketonet passim*) is the same phrase used for Joseph's robe in Genesis 37:3 — the robe that marked royal status and paternal favor. Here it marks the virgin daughters of the king. Tamar tearing that robe is a public performance of violated status: she is no longer what the robe signified. The ashes on her head and the hand on her head (13:19) are the full mourning vocabulary of the ancient Near East. She walks away 'crying aloud' (*zaaq*) — the same word used for the cry of the oppressed that ascends to God in Exodus 3:7 and throughout the Psalms.\n\nAbsalom's response in v. 20 is among the most troubling in the chapter. 'Keep silent, my sister; he is your brother; do not take this matter to heart.' Commentators are divided on whether Absalom's silence counsel is pastoral protection (he is concealing her shame from further public exposure) or personal agendum (silencing the matter serves his own eventual plans for vengeance more than it serves Tamar). The text does not clarify. What is clear is that Tamar's public cry ends here — she is silenced into Absalom's house and the word *shamem* closes her story in this chapter. *Shamem* is the prophetic word for a city made desolate by military destruction (Ezekiel 36:4; Lamentations 1:16; Isaiah 54:1). Applied to a human being, it is almost unbearable in its force.\n\nDavid's response in v. 21 is the chapter's most discussed lacuna. 'He was very angry' (*charah*) — and the verse ends. No action, no rebuke, no legal process, no pastoral intervention for Tamar. The LXX Codex Vaticanus adds: 'but he did not grieve the spirit of his son Amnon, because he loved him, for he was his firstborn.' If this gloss reflects original text, it confirms what the MT implies: David's love for his firstborn paralyzed his justice. The deeper theological point, developed by Calvin and Spurgeon alike, is that David's own unaddressed guilt over Bathsheba and Uriah has disabled his capacity to confront the same pattern in his son. A man who took another man's wife by coercive power cannot bring himself to name his son's coercive taking as what it is."
