        "excerpt": "Absalom commanded his servants, saying, 'See now, when Amnon's heart is merry with wine, and when I say to you, Strike Amnon, then put him to death.'",
        "body": "The murder scene is constructed as a deliberate echo of the rape. Both acts are engineered through deception and a domestic setting. Both use hospitality as a weapon. Both reveal a character who has been planning while performing normalcy. Absalom invites all the king's sons to a sheepshearing feast — a festive occasion that provides both social cover and the loosening of wine (13:28). His attempt to include David himself (13:24-25) may be a final test of how closely David is attending to family dynamics; David's refusal and his subsequent yielding of Amnon (13:26-27) again shows a father who is easily managed by a determined son.\n\nAbsalom's instructions to his servants in v. 28 are chilling in their military precision: 'when Amnon's heart is merry with wine... Strike Amnon, then put him to death. Do not fear; have not I myself commanded you? Be courageous and be valiant.' The last two phrases are the language of holy war — the same vocabulary Moses and Joshua use to commission troops for battle (Deuteronomy 31:6-7; Joshua 1:6-9). Absalom has framed a private murder in the language of military obedience. The theological perversion is exact: he appropriates the rhetoric of divine command to execute personal vengeance.\n\nJonadab's appearance in vv. 32-35 is one of the most theologically disturbing moments in the chapter. He knows immediately — before the other sons return — that only Amnon is dead and that 'by the intent of Absalom this has been determined since the day that he violated his sister Tamar.' Jonadab has known about the premeditation for two years. He was present at the beginning (the rape's engineering) and present at the end (the murder's explanation). His calm is the calm of a man who has been watching a script he helped write. He engineered Amnon's access to Tamar in chapter 1 of this story; he explains Absalom's vengeance in chapter 2 — and suffers no recorded consequence in either. The narrator offers no comment on him. The silence is damning."
