        "number": 5,
        "title": "Exile and longing — the incomplete grief of a dynasty undone",
        "range": "13:36-39",
        "excerpt": "The heart of King David longed to go out to Absalom; for he was comforted concerning Amnon, since he was dead.",
        "body": "The chapter's final four verses constitute one of the most theologically complex endings in Samuel. David and his servants weep 'very bitterly' at the return of the surviving princes (13:36). Then the narrative shifts immediately to Absalom's flight to Geshur — to his maternal grandfather Talmai, king of Geshur (13:37; cf. 3:3). The geography is precise: Geshur is beyond Israel's jurisdiction, beyond David's reach, behind an international boundary.\n\nDavid 'mourned for his son every day' (13:37). The pronoun reference is deliberately ambiguous — is it for Amnon (the dead son) or for Absalom (the exiled son)? The following clause clarifies partially: 'the heart of King David longed to go out to Absalom; for he was comforted concerning Amnon, since he was dead' (13:39). David has processed his grief for Amnon; his unresolved longing is now for Absalom. He yearns (*kalah* — the heart 'consumed itself,' or 'was spent') for a reconciliation he cannot bring himself to initiate and that Absalom, in exile, cannot offer. This emotional paralysis will last three years (13:38) and require Joab's intervention to break (14:1-24).\n\nThe theological weight of this ending is enormous. David — the man after God's own heart, the poet-king, the military genius — is rendered helpless by the harvest of his own sin. He cannot punish Amnon (whom he loved as firstborn and whose sin mirrored his own), cannot restore Tamar (who remains *shamem*), cannot reach Absalom (who has retreated beyond his authority). The three-year period of exile mirrors the three days of plague in 24:13, the three years of famine in 21:1, and the three years of Absalom's eventual exile after his return (14:28) — the number three in Samuel's narrative theology marking a sustained period of painful suspension. The word *nacham* in 13:39 ('he was comforted concerning Amnon') is the same word used for God's 'regret' in 1 Samuel 15:11 — the word carries the sense of emotional turning, of grief that has been worked through and released. David has mourned Amnon to completion. He has not yet begun to mourn what his own sin has cost the living.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Kalah* (v.39, 'longed') is a strong verb meaning to complete, finish, be spent — the heart is 'consumed' toward Absalom. *Nacham* (comforted) is the same root as 'comfort' in Isaiah 40:1 and the name Nahum; it carries the sense of being turned, emotionally repositioned. *Shamem* (13:20) — the word left hanging over Tamar as the chapter ends — is the prophets' word for a city razed to ruins. The chapter ends with the king's heart consumed toward the murderer and the primary victim last described as a human wasteland."
